03526nam a22005775i 9780823295838DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222000nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232958387 a10.1515/97808232958382doi  a(DE-B1597)626432  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPHI0070002bisacsh1 aGlazebrook, Trish, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHeidegger's Philosophy of Science /cTrish Glazebrook. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPerspectives in Continental Philosophy0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book concerns itself with an issue that is not sufficiently addressed in the literature: Heidegger’s philosophy of science. Although a great deal of attention is paid to Heidegger’s later critique of technology, no one has systematically studied how he understood “science.” Many readers will be surprised to learn, through this book, that Heidegger developed the essentials of a fairly sophisticated philosophy of science, one that in many ways invites comparison with that of Thomas Kuhn. Glazebrook demonstrates that Heidegger’s philosophy of science is not neatly divided into “early” and “late” (or “Heidegger I” and “Heidegger II”) but is, rather, an ongoing development over at least three periods, bound together as an analysis of modern science and an uncovering of other possibilities for understanding nature. Glazebrook states in her introduction, “This reading of Heidegger is radical. It cuts to the root of his thinking, for I argue that what are taken to be Heidegger’s many and significant contributions to philosophy—that is, his overcoming of metaphysics, his rereading of the ancients, his critique of technology and representational thinking, his vision and revision of language, truth, and thinking—have at their core an inquiry into science that drove his thinking for sixty years. I am not arguing for a new reading of a few texts, or for adjustments and refinements of existing readings of Heideggger. Rather, I am bringing to light a new basis on which to interpret his work as a whole.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Free Will & Determinism.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082329583840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823295838423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823295838/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK